article.headline: Jackson posts double-double for Lady Vols
article.linkText: Jackson answers Summitt's call to lead Tennessee
article.story:
KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Tennessee coach Pat Summitt entrusted
two tough duties to Gwen Jackson against Mississippi State (No. 13 ESPN/USA Today, No. 14 AP).

	   Jackson had to provide the inside scoring for the fourth-ranked
Volunteers and defend LaToya Thomas, the Lady Bulldogs' top scorer.

	   Jackson scored 18 of her 25 points in the second half and
grabbed 12 rebounds as Tennessee outlasted Mississippi State 82-68 on Sunday.

	   The Lady Vols (16-3, 5-0 Southeastern Conference) improved their
record over the Lady Bulldogs (14-4, 3-2) to 20-0, but had to work
hard into the second half to win their 43rd straight conference
home game.

	   Last year, Tennessee needed Kara Lawson's buzzer-beater to pull
out an 80-78 win. Mississippi State tried to make it close again
this year but couldn't stop the Lady Vols in the end.

	   At the start Summitt's defensive idea didn't seem too clever
since Jackson and reserve Shyra Ely both picked up two early fouls
guarding Thomas, but Summitt stayed with Jackson.

	   "She's a senior and has been playing extremely well with a lot
of confidence. I questioned whether or not I should have left her
on Thomas. I think she worked harder because she had the two fouls
to limit touches as opposed to staying behind and guarding her
after she got the ball,'' Summitt said. "She seemed more
aggressive and responded very well.''

	   Mississippi State, the only SEC team that has never beaten
Tennessee, trailed most of the first half but came out in the
second half with a 9-0 run to tie the game at 38.

	   After Jackson made a basket to put Tennessee ahead, the Lady
Bulldogs took their first lead of the game since 6-5 when Blessing
Chekwa converted a three-point play with 17:23 left.

	   The Lady Vols regained the lead and used an 8-2 run to push
their lead to seven. During the spurt, Tennessee worked its motion
offense perfectly and was able to have Jackson post up. She made
three straight shots, as the Lady Vols went ahead 52-45 with 13:42
remaining.

	   Mississippi State cut it to three again, but didn't get any
closer as Tennessee responded with an 11-4 run for a 10-point lead.

	   "We did a great job during the first few minutes of the second
half, but Tennessee kept its composure and weathered our runs,''
Mississippi State coach Sharon Fanning said. "We need to play with
more composure for several more minutes to have a different
result.''

	   Thomas managed to go over her average of 24.4 points a game with
28 while Tan White added 14 for the Lady Bulldogs.

	   "It's an honor to play against LaToya. She's an awesome player.
You're not going to keep her from scoring,'' Jackson said.

	   Lawson got the duty of guarding White, Mississippi State's
second-leading scorer, in the second half.

	   "Both Kara and Gwen stepped up big. They were aggressive,''
Summitt said. "They were guarding Mississippi State's two best
players. They were making plays at both ends. That's what you
expect your seniors to do.''

	   Lawson added 15 points and Shanna Zolman had 14 for Tennessee.

	   Tennessee led by nine at halftime after finishing the half with
a 7-1 run.

	   Mississippi State kept the game close early by matching the Lady
Vols' speed and hustle and despite having White on the bench with
three fouls.

	   The Lady Bulldogs led briefly at the beginning of the game but
never let Tennessee's lead get higher than seven until the end of
the first half.

	   Rebecca Kates hit a 3 with 4:06 left to cut the lead to three,
but Robinson had a basket and Zolman hit a 3 and another jumper to
give Tennessee a 38-29 lead at halftime.
